FMAttack: Exploiting the Unauthenticated CXL Fabric Manager Control Plane

Abstract

Compute Express Link (CXL) 3.x introduces the Fabric Manager (FM) as the privileged orchestration entity responsible for topology configuration, dynamic capacity allocation, and management command routing across disaggregated memory fabrics. While existing CXL security mechanisms such as SPDM and Trusted Security Protocol (TSP) protect device identity and memory confidentiality, the Fabric Manager control plane remains largely outside the formal security perimeter. In this paper, we demonstrate that unauthenticated Fabric Manager API (FMAPI) operations enable cross-tenant attacks capable of compromising confidentiality, integrity, and availability of CXL resources. We identify three critical attack classes: cross-tenant device reassignment, fabric-level denial-of-service, and unauthorized Dynamic Capacity Device (DCD) memory reallocation. To evaluate the practical impact, we implement a high-fidelity CXL fabric emulator incorporating virtual CXL switches, vPPBs, DCD memory pools, and FMAPI command handlers. Experimental results show that all attacks succeed with 100% reliability and require only microseconds of execution time. We further propose ZTFM (Zero-Trust Fabric Manager), a software-only defense architecture that combines SPDM-bound authentication, resource ownership enforcement, and semantic command validation. ZTFM blocks all identified attacks while introducing less than 5 μs overhead per FMAPI transaction. Our results demonstrate that FM control-plane security must become a first-class design requirement for future CXL deployments.

Keywords—CXL, Fabric Manager, FMAPI, Memory Disaggregation, Security, DCD, Multi-Tenant Systems

